    {
      "id": "ww97JNap2lYc5bcpGD-bx",
      "type": "text",
      "x": -1447.4121985836482,
      "y": -3017.590263277803,
      "width": 409.9267444606247,
      "height": 252.78348950518347,
      "angle": 0,
      "strokeColor": "#1e1e1e",
      "backgroundColor": "transparent",
      "fillStyle": "solid",
      "strokeWidth": 2,
      "strokeStyle": "solid",
      "roughness": 0,
      "opacity": 100,
      "groupIds": [],
      "frameId": null,
      "index": "b5t",
      "roundness": null,
      "seed": 91134455,
      "version": 1130,
      "versionNonce": 916920665,
      "isDeleted": false,
      "boundElements": null,
      "updated": 1774803060162,
      "link": null,
      "locked": false,
      "text": "DarkMatter\nThe package manager and plugin standard for AI agents.\nThe problem:\nRight now, every AI agent is a snowflake. When someone builds an agent, it expects inputs formatted a certain\nway. Each one has its own run command. Some only work inside a specific framework like LangChain or CrewAI.\nSome are only compatible within certain environments.\nIf you want to combine two agents built by different people, you're writing glue code. Custom plumbing just to\nget them talking to each other. And if you swap one out for a different agent, you start over.\nIt's the equivalent of every USB device needing its own proprietary port.\nThe solution:\nDarkMatter is the USB standard for AI agents.\nIt's a minimal contract that standardizes three things:\n1. Agent Identity (the manifest)\nEvery agent ships with a standard manifest declaring who it is, what it does, what version it is, and what it\nneeds. Think package.json but for agents.\n2. Run Interface (the port)\nOne universal way to call any agent. Input goes in, result comes out, always the same shape. No matter who\nbuilt it, no matter what framework they used. You call it the same way every time.\n3. Tool Integration (the plugins)\nA standard format for tools that agents can use. Search, APIs, calculators, whatever. Any tool works with any\nagent. Plug and play, no rewiring.\nWhat this means in practice:\nTeams stop rebuilding integration plumbing every time they want to combine agents. Instead, they treat agents\nlike installable, reusable packages. Build one, register it, and anyone can discover it, run it, chain it with other\nagents, or swap it out. Zero glue code.",
      "fontSize": 8.089071664165871,
      "fontFamily": 6,
      "textAlign": "left",
      "verticalAlign": "top",
      "containerId": null,
      "originalText": "DarkMatter\nThe package manager and plugin standard for AI agents.\nThe problem:\nRight now, every AI agent is a snowflake. When someone builds an agent, it expects inputs formatted a certain way. Each one has its own run command. Some only work inside a specific framework like LangChain or CrewAI. Some are only compatible within certain environments.\nIf you want to combine two agents built by different people, you're writing glue code. Custom plumbing just to get them talking to each other. And if you swap one out for a different agent, you start over.\nIt's the equivalent of every USB device needing its own proprietary port.\nThe solution:\nDarkMatter is the USB standard for AI agents.\nIt's a minimal contract that standardizes three things:\n1. Agent Identity (the manifest)\nEvery agent ships with a standard manifest declaring who it is, what it does, what version it is, and what it needs. Think package.json but for agents.\n2. Run Interface (the port)\nOne universal way to call any agent. Input goes in, result comes out, always the same shape. No matter who built it, no matter what framework they used. You call it the same way every time.\n3. Tool Integration (the plugins)\nA standard format for tools that agents can use. Search, APIs, calculators, whatever. Any tool works with any agent. Plug and play, no rewiring.\nWhat this means in practice:\nTeams stop rebuilding integration plumbing every time they want to combine agents. Instead, they treat agents like installable, reusable packages. Build one, register it, and anyone can discover it, run it, chain it with other agents, or swap it out. Zero glue code.",
      "autoResize": false,
      "lineHeight": 1.25
    },
